{{wikisource1911Enc|Aaron's Rod}}
==English==

===Etymology===
With reference to Numbers 17:8 (‘And it came to pass, that on the morrow Moses went into the tabernacle of witness; and, behold, the rod of Aaron for the house of Levi was budded, and brought forth buds, and bloomed blossoms, and yielded almonds.’  King James Version).

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|RP}} {{IPA|/ˈɜːɹ.ənz ɹɒd/|/ˈæɹ.ənz ɹɒd/}}
* {{a|GenAm}} {{IPA|/ˈɜɹ.ənz ɹɑd/|/ˈæɹ.ənz ɹɑd/}}

===Noun===
{{en-noun|s|-}}

# {{context|botany}} Any of various plants with a tall flowering stem; especially the [[great mullein]], or [[hag-taper]], and the [[golden-rod]].{{defdate|Mid 18<sup>th</sup> century.}}<ref name=SOED>Brown, Lesley, (2003)</ref>
# {{context|architecture}} A [[rod]]-shaped [[molding]] decorated with an entwined snake, and sometimes leaves, vines, and/or scrolls.
# {{context|archaic}} A rod with one serpent twined around it, as used by Aaron (differing from the [[caduceus]] of Mercury, which has two serpents).

